    2. http://www.robweir.com/blog/
    3. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenDocument


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Linus on GIT and SCM                                               |
|   from the strong-opinions dept.                                   |
|   posted by kdawson on Saturday June 02, @22:13 (Software)         |
|   http://developers.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/004214    |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader sends us to a blog posting (with the YouTube video
embedded) about Linus Torvalds' talk at Google a few weeks back. [0]Linus
talked about developing GIT, the source control system used by the Linux
kernel developers, and exhibited his characteristic strong opinions on
subjects around SCM, by which he means "Source Code Management." SCM is a
subject that coders are either passionate about or bored by. Linus
appears to be in the former camp. Here is his take on Subversion:
"Subversion has been the most pointless project ever started...
Subversion used to say, 'CVS done right.' With that slogan there is
nowhere you can go. There is no way to do CVS right."

Discuss this story at:
    http://developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/004214

Links:
    0. http://codicesoftware.blogspot.com/2007/05/linus-torvalds-on-git-and-scm.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Wreck of Australian Warship HMAS Sydney Found?                     |
|   from the frieght-and-salvage dept.                               |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @00:09 (Space)              |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/0018216      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Mendy writes "Tim Ankers, a British archaeologist, claims to have
[0]found the wreck of the HMAS Sydney, lost with all hands in the Indian
Ocean during World War II. He says that he's done this from the comfort
of his home using software he wrote called Merlindown, which can analyze
satellite photographs at different wavelengths to 'peer 75 meters into
the earth and 16,000 meters beneath the seas.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/0018216

Links:
    0. http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/science/article1873026.ece


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| TiVo Says It Could Suffer Under GPLv3                              |
|   from the no-prevention-of-hacking dept.                          |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @02:52 (Television)         |
|   http://linux.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/02/2219230        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Preedit writes to tell us that those busy folks over at InformationWeek
have been scrutinizing yet more SEC filings, and [0]Novell and Microsoft
aren't the only ones concerned about certain provisions in the final
draft of GPLv3. [1]TiVo worries too. The problem is that TiVo boxes are
Linux-based. They're also designed to shut down if the software is hacked
by users trying to circumvent DRM features. But GPLv3 would prohibit
TiVo's no-tamper setup. "If the currently proposed version of GPLv3 is
widely adopted, we may be unable to incorporate future enhancements to
the GNU/Linux operating system into our software, which could adversely
affect our business," TiVo warns in a regulatory filing cited by
InformationWeek."

Discuss this story at:
    http://linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/02/2219230

Links:
    0. http://linux.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/02/2138241&tid=223
    1. http://www.informationweek.com/industries/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=199900263


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| The Big Bang Vs. the Big Rumble                                    |
|   from the ekpyrotic-upstart dept.                                 |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @05:33 (Math)               |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/0117208      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

WBUR radio in Boston hosts [0]a talk with two physicists, Alan Guth and
Neil Turok, who represent, respectively, the consensus theory of the
inflationary Big Bang and an upstart theory of the initiation of the
universe in the collision of two three-dimensional "branes." [1]Turok and
[2]Paul Steinhardt developed their "Ekpyrotic proposal" out of the
mathematics behind string theory. In the audio the two physicists are
perhaps more respectful of one another's views than the host wishes them
to be. If you ignore the "let's you and him fight" framing of the debate,
you will hear some interesting physics elucidated.

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/0117208

Links:
    0. http://www.onpointradio.org/shows/2007/05/20070531_b_main.asp
    1. http://huehueteotl.wordpress.com/2007/05/21/the-cyclic-universe-a-talk-with-neil-turok/
    2. http://www.physics.princeton.edu/~steinh/npr/


