| Space Elevator Company LiftPort In Trouble                         |
|   from the going-dwn dept.                                         |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @12:53 (Space)              |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/1648214      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]TropicalCoder writes "[1]The LiftPort Group, founded four years ago
with the lofty dream of building a stairway to heaven, has seemingly
reached the end the line. The dream was to develop a ribbon of carbon
nanotubes 100,000 km long, anchored to the Earth's surface and with a
counterweight in space, providing a permanent bridge to orbit. Elevator
cars would be robotic 'lifters' which would climb the ribbon to deliver
cargo and eventually people to orbit or beyond. Now LiftPort has all but
[2]run out of funds, and the State of Washington's Securities Division
has entered a [3]Statement of Charges (PDF) against LiftPort Inc. dba
LiftPort Group and founder Michael Laine."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/1648214

Links:
    0. http://www.magma.ca/~gtaylor/
    1. http://www.liftport.com/
    2. http://www.spaceelevator.com/archives/2007/05/liftport_tries.html
    3. http://www.dfi.wa.gov/sd/orders/S-06-077-07-SC01.pdf


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Guitartabs.com Suspends Under Legal Pressure                       |
|   from the not-another-mpaa dept.                                  |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @13:59 (Music)              |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/1747256          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Music publishers are stepping up their campaign to [0]remove guitar
tablature from the Net. Recently [1]Guitartabs.com received a nastygram
from lawyers for the National Music Publishers Association and The Music
Publishers Association of America. These organizations want to stretch
the definition of their intellectual property to include by-ear
transcriptions of music. Guitartabs.com is currently not offering
tablature while the owner evaluates his legal options.

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/1747256

Links:
    0. http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/15/2149224&tid=141
    1. http://www.guitartabs.com/nmpa.php


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Russia Claims IP Rights In Manufacture of AK-47                    |
|   from the kalashnikov's-yer-uncle dept.                           |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @15:01 (Patents)            |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/1840203          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Daniel Dvorkin writes "In the latest example of over-the-top
intellectual property demands, [1]Russia wants licensing fees for the
production of AK-47s. According to first deputy prime minister Sergei
Ivanov, the unlicensed production of Kalashnikovs (which have been around
in very nearly their current form for 60 years) in ex-Soviet Bloc
countries is 'intellectual piracy.' A giant but declining power starts
demanding royalties on commonly used methods and materials that are
widely understood, well known, and by any reasonable standard have long
been in the public domain — does this sound familiar?" Wikipedia notes
that the Izhevsk Machine Tool Factory in Russia [2]obtained a patent on
the manufacture of the AK-47 in 1999.

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/1840203

Links:
    0. http://www.sff.net/people/daniel.dvorkin
    1. http://en.rian.ru/russia/20070316/62123005.html
    2. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AK_47


