+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Google et al. Want 700 MHz Auction Opened Up                       |
|   from the third-helping-of-pipes dept.                            |
|   posted by kdawson on Sunday June 03, @19:13 (Wireless Networking)|
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/03/2014248     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

The 700 MHz spectrum could give birth to the much-anticipated third pipe,
but phone and cable lobbyists are currently pressuring the FCC to sell
companies like AT&T and Verizon our airwaves — in a [0]flawed auction
process — so they can hoard this valuable spectrum and stifle competitive
alternatives to their networks. Google and other would-be providers
[1]are not taking it lying down. They want the FCC to mandate that
whoever wins the auction be required to sell access to those airwaves, at
wholesale prices, to anyone wanting to provide broadband Internet
service. They also want anonymous auctions to prevent the giant
incumbents from manipulating the results against small players (as they
have done in the past).

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/03/2014248

Links:
    0. http://www.publicknowledge.org/node/962
    1. http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060300458.html



